To add a password reset functionality in your React Native Expo application using Firebase, you can follow these steps:

1. Import the `auth` module from `firebase`.

```js
import { firebase } from '../Firebase/firebase';
import 'firebase/compat/auth';
```

2. Add a `handleResetPassword` function that uses the `sendPasswordResetEmail` method from Firebase `auth` to send a password reset email to the provided email address.

```js
const handleResetPassword = () => {
    firebase.auth().sendPasswordResetEmail(email)
    .then(() => {
        Alert.alert('Успех!', 'Письмо с инструкциями отправлено на указанный адрес');
    })
    .catch((error) => {
        const errorMessage = error.message;
        console.log(errorMessage);
        Alert.alert('Ошибка!', errorMessage);
    });
};
```

3. Create a new `Pressable` component that executes the `handleResetPassword` function when pressed.

```js
<Pressable style={gStyle.AuthForgotPassword} onPress={handleResetPassword}>
    <Text style={gStyle.AuthPass}>Забыли пароль?</Text>
</Pressable>
```

With these steps, your users should be able to reset their password by providing their email address and clicking on the 'Reset Password' button. They will receive an email with instructions on how to reset their password.

Yes, you can allow admins of your Firebase project to add posts in the app. Here are the steps to accomplish this:

1. Create a Firebase Cloud Firestore collection to store the posts data. 

```js
import { firebase } from '../Firebase/firebase';
import 'firebase/compat/auth';
import 'firebase/compat/database';
import 'firebase/compat/firestore';
import React, {useState, useEffect} from 'react';

// create a reference to the posts collection
const postsRef = firebase.firestore().collection('posts');
```

2. Create a form to collect data from the admin.

```js
const [title, setTitle] = useState('');
const [content, setContent] = useState('');

return(
  <View>
    <Text>Enter post details below:</Text>
    <TextInput
      placeholder="Title"
      onChangeText={setTitle}
      value={title}
    />
    <TextInput
      placeholder="Content"
      multiline={true}
      numberOfLines={5}
      onChangeText={setContent}
      value={content}
    />
    <Button title="Submit Post" onPress={submitPost}/>
  </View>
);
```

3. Create a function to handle the form submission and add the post to the Firestore collection.

```js
const submitPost = () => {
  // add new post to the posts collection
  postsRef.add({
    title: title,
    content: content,
    date: new Date().toISOString(),
  })
  .then(() => {
    setTitle('');
    setContent('');
    console.log('Post added successfully!');
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.log(error);
  });
};
```

4. Authenticate the admin and restrict access to the post submission form to admins only.

You can use Firebase Authentication to authenticate admins and then use Firebase Security Rules to restrict access to the post submission form to authenticated admins only. You can use custom claims to identify admins and add custom rules to prevent non-admins from accessing the form.

Here's an example of how to add a custom claim to a user:

```js
const userID = firebase.auth().currentUser.uid;
firebase.auth().currentUser.getIdTokenResult()
  .then((idTokenResult) => {
    const isAdmin = idTokenResult.claims.admin;
    // set isAdmin to true for an admin user
    if(isAdmin){
      firebase.auth().currentUser.setCustomClaim({admin: true});
    }
  });
```

You can then use the `admin` custom claim in your Firebase Security Rules to restrict access to the post submission form or the entire Firestore collection.

With these steps, admins of your Firebase project will be able to add posts to the Firestore collection through the app. Make sure to implement appropriate security measures as necessary.

